#Text=I got to meet one of the stardust directors in March during the Texas Aerospace Scholars program at JSC .
#Text=She talked about searching for meteors in Antarctica , one that were unblemished by Earth conditions .
#Text=Is that our best chance of finding new information on comets and asteroids ?
#Text=Or will more Stardust programs be our best solution ?
#Text=That 's a really good question .
#Text=Much will depend on what we learn during this official " Preliminary Examination " period for the cometary analysis .

column1: #Text=Aerogel capture is pretty darn good , but it 's not perfect and things are altered during capture in ways that we 're still understanding .
#Text=I think that much also depends on what question you 're asking .
#Text=For example , some of the most important science is done by measuring the relative abundances of isotopes in samples , and these are not affected ( at least not much ) by capture into aerogel .
#Text=Also , she talked about how some of the agencies that they gave samples to had lost or destroyed 2-3 samples while trying to analyze them .
#Text=That one , in fact , had been statically charged , and stuck to the side of the microscope lens and they spent over an hour looking for it .
#Text=Is that really our biggest danger ?
#Text=Giving out samples as a show of good faith , and not letting NASA example all samples collected ?
#Text=These will be the first measurements , probably , that we 'll make on the interstellar dust
#Text=There is always a risk of loss .
#Text=Fortunately for the cometary samples there is quite a lot there , so it 's not a disaster .

#Text=NASA has some analytical capabilities , particularly at JSC , but the vast majority of the analytical capability in the community is not at NASA but is at universities , government labs and other institutions all over the world .
#Text=I should also point out that practically every analytical technique is destructive at some level . ( There are a few exceptions , but not many . )
#Text=The problem with meteorites is that except in a very few cases , we do n't know where they specifically came from .
#Text=So having a sample that we know for sure is from the comet is golden !
#Text=I am currently working on my Bachelor 's in computer science , with a minor in astronomy .
#Text=Do you see successes of programs like Stardust to open up more private space exploration positions for people such as myself .
#Text=Even though I 'm not in the typical " space " fields of education ?
#Text=Can you elaborate on your question a little — I 'm not sure that I understand ...

#Text=Well , while at JSC I learned that they mostly want Engineers , and a few science grads , and I worry that my computer science degree with not be very valuable , as the NASA rep told me only 1 % of the applicants for their work study program are CS majors .
#Text=I 'm just curious as to your thoughts on if CS majors will be more in demand now that projects like Stardust and the Mars missions have been great successes ?
#Text=Have you seen a trend towards more private businesses moving in that direction , especially with President Bush 's statement of Man on the Moon in 2015 ?
